{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624444"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:18:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:18:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16902"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16902"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.52,0,0,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5764"},{"type":"tags","id":"7690"},{"type":"tags","id":"10789"},{"type":"tags","id":"10798"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22657"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECRISPR-Cas9 technology has revolutionised genetic engineering by allowing precise DNA modifications. However, its potential use in human embryos has sparked significant ethical debate in the scientific community.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the current ethical consensus regarding appropriate human gene editing using CRISPR technology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete prohibition of all gene editing","Therapeutic use in somatic cells only","Use in animal trials only","Unrestricted use in both somatic and germline cells","Research use in cell lines only"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe current ethical consensus supports \u003Cstrong\u003Etherapeutic use in somatic cells only\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach allows treatment of genetic diseases in non-reproductive cells while avoiding heritable modifications. Somatic cell modifications affect only the treated individual and cannot be passed to future generations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete prohibition of all gene editing\u003C/strong\u003E - This would prevent beneficial therapeutic applications that could treat serious genetic conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse in animal trials only\u003C/strong\u003E - While animal trials are important for research, research into human somatic cell applications beyond animal studies is generally supported by the scientific community\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnrestricted use in both somatic and germline cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This would pose unacceptable risks, both medically and ethically, of heritable modifications with unknown consequences for future generations,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResearch use in cell lines only\u003C/strong\u003E - While this is an important application, the current consensus allows for broader therapeutic applications in somatic cells beyond just research\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost regulatory bodies and scientific organisations support continued research into somatic cell gene therapy while maintaining restrictions on germline modifications until safety, efficacy, and ethical implications are better understood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing raises ethical concerns about germline modifications that can be inherited by future generations.","Current international guidelines prohibit clinical applications of human germline gene editing.","Somatic cell gene editing for therapeutic purposes is generally considered more ethically acceptable than germline modifications."],"references":["Ayano\u011flu FB, El\u00e7in AE, El\u00e7in YM. Bioethical issues in genome editing by CRISPR-Cas9 technology. Turk J Biol. 2020 Apr 2;44(2):110-120. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7129066/","Li T, Yang Y, Qi H, et al. CRISPR/Cas9 therapeutics: Progress and Prospects. Signal Transduction and Targeted Therapy. 2023;8(1):1-23. doi:https://doi.org/10.1038/s41392-023-01309-7","Wang SW, Gao C, Zheng YM, et al. Current applications and future perspective of CRISPR/Cas9 gene editing in cancer. Molecular Cancer. 2022;21(1). doi:https://doi.org/10.1186/s12943-022-01518-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16902"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T09:43:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T09:43:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9592"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76687"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount